  "prompt": "Why is every last name you see a male name?",
  "response": "The perception that last names are primarily male names can be rooted in historical and cultural practices regarding naming conventions. Historically, many societies have followed a patrilineal system, where family names are passed down through the male line. This has often resulted in surnames being associated with male figures, as names were traditionally inherited from fathers.\n\nAdditionally, in many cultures, women traditionally took on their husband's surname after marriage, which reinforced the notion that surnames are male-oriented. Even in cultures where women retain their maiden names, the naming conventions can still reflect a male lineage.\n\nIt's important to note that attitudes and practices regarding surnames are evolving. In contemporary society, there is a growing acceptance of different naming practices, including hyphenated surnames, the use of mother's surnames, and even individuals choosing to keep their own last names after marriage. These changes are contributing to a more diverse understanding of names and their implications regarding gender.",
